Data Pre-Processing Chapter Takeaways

Get the Book

There is an excellent book called Applied Predictive Modeling and if you are interested in machine learning and statistics, then check it out at the link.

Intro

  • Tree-based models are notably insensitive to the characteristics of the predictor data
  • Combinations of predictors can sometimes be more effectie than using the individual values
    • The ratio of two predictors may be more effective than using two independent predictors

Centering and Scaling

To center a predictor variable, the average predictor value is subtracted from all values. Thus, the data has \(0\) mean.

rm(list = ls())
library(ggplot2)
library(ggthemes)

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 10) +
  ggtitle("MPG Uncentered") +
  theme_economist()

center = function(vector) {
  vector - mean(vector)
}
mpgCent = center(mtcars$mpg)
mpgCent = data.frame( mpgCent = mpgCent)

ggplot(mpgCent, aes(x = mpgCent)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 10) +
  ggtitle("MPG Centered") +
  theme_economist()

To scale a variable, the vector is divided by its standard deviation. Here, we are coercing the data to have a standard deviation of 1.

scaled = function(vector) {
  vector/sd(vector)
}
mpgScale = scaled(mtcars$mpg)
mpgScale = data.frame( mpgScale = mpgScale)

ggplot(mpgScale, aes(x = mpgScale)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 10) +
  ggtitle("MPG Scaled") +
  theme_economist()

To center and scale data, comnbine the top two techniques.

cAndS = function(vector) {
  center(vector)/sd(center(vector))
}

mpgCandS = cAndS(mtcars$mpg)
mpgCandS = data.frame( mpgCandS = mpgCandS)

ggplot(mpgCandS, aes(x = mpgCandS)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 10) +
  ggtitle("MPG Centered and Scaled") +
  theme_economist()

Resolving Skewness

Skewed data can be troublesome. Consider a highly skewed dataset where 95% of the data is labeled 1, 4% is labeled 2 and 1% labeled 3. There is a severe lack of variability in the data and thus little to no information. Dat that is not too heavily skewed can be adjusted to look a bit normal by taking the log, root, or inverse. A general rule of thumb is that data whose majority value divided by second majority is greater than 20, its skewed. In the example above, the ratio is \(\frac{95}{4} = 23.5\). If a predictor is roughly normal, the skew will be close to 0.

The formula for skewness is:

\[ \text{skew} = \frac{\sum(x_i-\bar{x})^3}{(n-1)v^{3/2}} \\ \text{where}\:\;v = \frac{\sum(x_i-\bar{x})^2}{(n-1)} \]

where \(x\) is the predictor variable, \(n\) is the number of values, and \(\bar{x}\) is the sample mean of the predictor.

Lets load some data from my website which was taken from a Kaggle competition. You can find the link to the data here.

houses = read.csv("http://fdrennan.net/pages/pages2/datasets/housetrain.csv")

Here, we have some skewed data related to selling prices. The distribution makes intutitive sense. However, we can improve the distribution by taking the log of the distribution. Lets observe.

ggplot(houses, aes(x = SalePrice)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 100) +
  theme_economist() +
  ggtitle("Selling Prices of Homes: Normal")

ggplot(houses, aes(x = log(SalePrice))) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 100) +
  theme_economist() +
  ggtitle("Selling Prices of Homes: Log of Distribution")

Box-Cox Transformation

There is a good explanation of the Box-Cox transformation here.

This family of transformations is indexed by a parameter \(\lambda\), which will be shown in an example later.

\[ f(x) = \left\{ \begin{array}{ll} \frac{x^{\lambda}-1}{\lambda} & \text{if}\;\; \lambda \neq 0 \\ \text{log}(x) & \text{if}\;\; \lambda = 0 \end{array} \right. \]

Outliers

  • Tree based models tend to be resistant to missing values.
  • If a model is considered to be sensitive to outliers, one data transformation that can minimize the problem is the spatial sign.

\[ x^*_{ij} = \frac{x_{ij}}{\sqrt{\sum_{j=1}^{P}x^2_{ij}}} \]

Good explanation here from stack overflow. Code edited slightly using the ICSNP package.

n <- 10000
tmp <- data.frame(x=c(rnorm(n, 0, 0.02), -1, 1, 0.5),
                  y=c(rnorm(n, 0, 0.2), -1, 1, -2))

plot(tmp, asp=1, col=c(rep(1,n), 2, 3, 4), pch=19)
grid()

plot(ICSNP::spatial.sign(tmp), asp=1, col=c(rep(1,n), 2, 3, 4), pch=19)
grid()

Data Reduction and Feature Extraction

  • PCA is commonly used.
  • Generally, new predictors are functions of the original predictors. All the original predictors are needed to create the surrogate variables.
  • The primary advantage of PCA, and the reason that it has retained its populatrity as a data reduction method, is that it creates components that are uncorrelated.
  • Practitioners must understand the PCA seeks predictor-set variation without regard to any further understanding of the predictors.
  • To help PCA avoid summarizing distributional differences and predictor scale information, it is best ot first transform skewed predictors and then center and scale the predictors prior to performing PCA.
  • If the predictive relationship between the predictors and the response is not connected to the predictors variabliity, then the derived PCs will not provide a suitable relationship with the response. In this case, a supervised technique, like PLA will derive componentes while simultaneously considering the corresponding reponse.
  • In an automated model building process, the optimial number of components can be determined by cross-validation.
  • Skewed predictors can have an impact on PCA. Consider doing Box-Cox first and then after the transformations, center and scale and do PCA.

Missing Data

  • Missing values actually may represent something and should be encoded with a variable indivator.
  • Missing values may represent data in the form of individuals who couldnt finish the study related to events within the study. For example, someone in a medical study might have left because the medication made he or she worse off. Obviously, this is data that you would not want to miss.
  • A value may be missing because of a cutoff. Think an assay where there is a minimal detectable limit. In this case, use a random variable between 0 and the cutoff limit.
  • A few predictive models, especially tree-based techniques, can specifically account for missing dat.
  • For predictive models we are concerned about accuracy of the predictions rather than making valid inferences.
  • Prior to model trianing or the prediction of new samples, missing values are filled in using imputation. Note that this extra layer of models adds uncertainty.
  • One popular technique for imputation is a K-nearest neightbor model.

Between-Predictor Correlations

Multicollinearity, get rid of it. Read here.

  • Multicollinearity is when you have strong relationships between multiple predictors.
  • There are good reasons to avoid dat with highly correlated predictors. First, redundant predictors frequently add more complexity to the model than information they provide to the model.
  • Using highly correlated predictors in techniques like linear regression can result in highly unstable models.
x = 1:10
y = x*(1+rnorm(n = 10, mean = 0, sd = .1))
plot(x,y)

cor(x, y)
## [1] 0.9714641

x and y are clearly related. Collinear predictors can impact the variance of parameter estimates in a model, so a statistic called the variance inflation factor (VIF) can be sued to identify predictors that are impacted.

Another approach is to remove predictors below a certain threshold. The idea is to remove the predictors that have the most correlated relationships. Ths means that we want to eliminate the minimum number of predictors to achieve all pairwise correlations, say, less than 0.75. The code to do this will be shown below.

Adding Predictors

Sometimes it is better to split factors into binary vectors. For example, a column of male and female predictors may be better suited as a binary vector indicated \(1\) for male and \(0\) for female. Suppose there are three factors, cat, dog, and rabbit. The vector could be split into two vectors. One binary indicating cat, and another for dog. The Rabbit is implicit in the 0 values missing from cat and dog.

Binning Predictors

Dont do it. For example, people with a heart rate below 80, between 80 and 100, and greater than 100 as binary vectors.

Computing

Ok, lets dig into some cool functions.

Check out the package AppliedPredictiveModelings documentation here

train = read.csv("http://fdrennan.net/pages/pages2/datasets/housetrain.csv")

return_numeric = function(dataset) {
  # Splitting data into numeric columns.
  #################################################
  
  classes = sapply(dataset, class)

  numericCols = names(classes[classes != "factor"])
  originalNumeric = dataset[numericCols]
  originalNumeric
}

train = return_numeric(train)

# Removing a date column and id columns
response = train[39]
train=train[-c(1:2, 38,39)]

To determine which type of transformation should be used, the MASS package contains the boxcox function. The function estimates \(\lambda\) but does not create the transformed variables. A caret function, BoxCoxTrans can find the appropriate transformation and apply them to the new data. The data below GrLivArea is the above grade (ground) living area square feet for some homes.

library(e1071)
skewness(train$GrLivArea)
## [1] 1.363754
library(caret)
hist(train$GrLivArea, main = "Living Area before Box-Cox", xlab = "Square Feet")

BoxCoxTrans = BoxCoxTrans(train$GrLivArea)
BoxCoxTrans
## Box-Cox Transformation

## 
## Largest/Smallest: 16.9 
## Sample Skewness: 1.36 
## 
## Estimated Lambda: 0

predictedTransform = predict(BoxCoxTrans, train$GrLivArea)
hist(predictedTransform, main = "Living Area after Box-Cox", xlab = "Square Feet")

Another caret function, preProcess, applies this transformation to a set of predictors. The base R function prcomp can be used for PCA. In the code below, the data are centered and scaled prior to PCA. But first, given that there are many na values, Im going to use the impute function from the package e1071 in order to do a k-nearest neighbors approach in filling in NA values.

To Box-Cox transform, center, and scale the dat, then excecute PCA for signal extraction, the syntax would be:

trans = preProcess(trainImpute,
                   method = c("BoxCox", "center", "scale", "pca"))

To filter for near-zero variance predictors, the caret package function nearZeroVar will return the column numbers of any predictors that fulfill the conditions for removal

# A vector of integers to 
# is returned by the function nearZeroVar
transformed = transformed[-nearZeroVar(transformed)]

To visually examine the correlation structure of the data, use corrplot. The hclust paramter clusters variables with high correlations with one another.

correlations = cor(transformed)
library(corrplot)
corrplot(correlations, order = "hclust")

To filter based on correlations, the fundCorrelation function return column numbers denoting predictors that are recommened for deletion. That is, they are columns that are already explained by others. It helps remove multicollinearity from the data.

highCorr = findCorrelation(correlations, cutoff = .75)
head(highCorr)
## [1] 14 12 23  6
filteredTransformed = transformed[, -highCorr]

correlationFiltered = cor(filteredTransformed)
corrplot(correlationFiltered, order = "hclust")

3.1

The US Irvine Machine Learning Repository contains a dataset related to glass identification. The data consist of 214 glass samples labeled as one of seven categories. There are nine predictors, including the refractive index and percentages of eight elements: Na, Mg, Al, Si, K, Ca, Ba, and Fe.

The data can be accessed via:

library(mlbench)
data(Glass)

  • Using visualizations, explore the predictor variables to understand their distributions as well as the relationships between the predictors.
colNames = colnames(Glass)

for( i in 1:9) {
  gg = ggplot(Glass, aes(x = Glass[[i]])) +
  geom_histogram(bins = trunc(length(Glass[[i]])/2)) +
  ggtitle(paste0("Histogram of: ", colNames[i]), sub = paste("Skew = ", round(skewness(Glass[[i]]) , 3) )) +
    theme_economist()
  print(gg)
}

Mg has a clear outlier in the lower end of the distribution. Fe and Ba are highly skewed. Log transformations of Fe and Ba improve the distributions.

for( i in 8:9) {
  gg = ggplot(Glass, aes(x = log(Glass[[i]]))) +
  geom_histogram(bins = trunc(length(Glass[[i]])/2)) +
  ggtitle(paste0("Histogram of Log of: ", colNames[i]), sub = paste("Skew = ", round(skewness(Glass[[i]]) , 3) )) +
    theme_economist()
  print(gg)
}
